<div class='onepage'>
    <article>Final-ly, a once-promising startup
        that aimed to disrupt the funeral
        industry, has filed for bankruptcy.
        The company, which launched just three
        years ago, had raised over $10 million
        in funding and had garnered significant
        attention in the tech world.

        The idea behind Final-ly was to
        provide a more modern and affordable
        approach to funeral services, which can
        often be expensive and emotionally draining
        for families. The company offered a range of
        services, from direct cremation to traditional
        funerals, and used technology to streamline the
        process and reduce costs. Despite its initial
        promise, Final-ly struggled to gain traction
        in a crowded market. The company faced intense
        competition from established players in the funeral
        industry, who were quick to adapt to changing consumer
        preferences. In addition, the COVID-19 pandemic caused
        significant disruptions to the funeral industry, making
        it even more challenging for Final-ly to succeed.
        In a statement, Final-ly CEO John Smith expressed
        disappointment at the company's failure, but
        emphasized the positive impact it had on the
        industry. "We may not have succeeded in our
        mission to disrupt the funeral industry, but
        we are proud of the innovations we brought to
        the market and the conversations we started
        about the need for change," he said.
    
    </article>

    
